expanation:
Return on equity indicates the financial performance of the firm, which is the division of net income and stockholders' equity. The company's competitive advantage is identified by comparing its return on equity to the industry average. Insight into how the management of the firm is utilizing equity funding to expand the business may also be gained through ROE. The formula for computing the return on equity is:

{eq}\begin{aligned} \text{Return on Equity} &=\frac{\text{Net Income}}{\text{Average Shareholders' Equity}} \end{aligned} {/eq}

Net income is calculated before the distribution of dividends to common shareholders. It is also determined after preferred shareholder dividends and interest payments.

hint:
The return on assets shows the ratio that determines the firm's profitability relative to its total assets. The return on assets (ROA) statistic measures how efficiently a firm can use its assets to increase its net profits. The formula for computing the return on assets is:

{eq}\begin{aligned} \text{Return on Assets} &=\frac{\text{Net Income}}{\text{Average Total Assets}} \end{aligned} {/eq}

The company's net income is equivalent to the net earnings of the annual period. The average total assets are calculated by dividing the sum of the beginning total assets and the ending total assets by two.

