The correct answer is option d. A credit to gain in the amount of $2,500.

The net book value of the machine at the time of sale is computed as follows:

{eq}\begin{align*} &= \text{Original cost - accumulated depreciation} \\[0.3 cm] &= $12,000 - $9,000 \\[0.3 cm] &= $3,000 \end{align*} {/eq}

The gain or loss on the sale of the machine is computed as follows:

{eq}\begin{align*} &= \text{Sale value - net book value} \\[0.3 cm] &= $5,500 - $3,000 \\[0.3 cm] &= $2,500 \text{ positive value denotes a gain} \end{align*} {/eq}

An increase in assets or expenses is reported as a debit entry whereas an increase in liabilities or gains is reported as a credit entry. Since there is a gain of $2,500 on the disposal of the machine, it will be reported as a credit entry in the gains account.
